definition.value: An organophosphate oxoanion that is the pentaanionic form of adenosine 5'-tetraphosphate.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of pyridoxamine 5'-phosphate.
The dianion resulting from the removal of two protons from the phosphate group of 5-amino-6-(5-phospho-D-ribosylamino)uracil.
A quinolinemonocarboxylate that is the conjugate base of kynurenic acid
An L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained from L-2-aminohexanoic acid by transfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
Trianionic form of pyrroloquinoline quinol arising from deprotonation of the three carboxy groups.
A vinca alkaloid cation that is the conjugate acid of 17-O-deacetylvindoline.
The conjugate base of a nucleoside 3',5'-cyclic phosphate.
The conjugate base of dermatan sulfate, obtained by deprotonation of carboxy and sulfate groups.
An amino acid zwitterion of 3-aminoalanine where the 3-amino group is protonated.
An organophosphate oxoanion resulting from the removal of both protons from the phosphate group of 5-amino-1-(5-phospho-D-ribosyl)imidazole-4-carboxamide. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of N(omega)-phospho-L-arginine having anionic carboxy and phosphate groups and protonated amino and guanidino nitrogens.
An indole alkaloid cation that is the conjugate acid of 3-hydroxy-16-methoxy-2,3-dihydrotabersonine, obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino function; major species at pH 7.3.
A doubly-charged tricarboxylic acid anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxy groups and protonation of the amino group of 3-epi-3-hydroxymugineic acid.
The conjugate base of an N-acetyl-D-amino acid.
Conjugate base of an N-acyl-L-aspartic acid.
A member of the class of phenylureas that is N-(2-methoxyphenyl)urea in which one of the two protons on the free NH2 function has been replaced by a 2-naphthyl group.
